{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D46jGHkBn8U52ZLELXY6Dh","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good. I have now thoroughly explored the codebase. Let me compile the comprehensive implementation plan.\n\n---\n\n# SuperSearch Visualization Upgrade: Comprehensive Implementation Plan\n\n## 1. Current State Assessment\n\nThe file at `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/docs/index.html` is 795 lines, approximately 28.8 KB. It uses Three.js r128 via CDN, loads a 3.2 MB JSON file containing 21,263 material data points (fields: `x`, `y`, `tc`, `cluster`, `atomic_mass`, `atomic_radius`, `valence`) and 34 sparse regions (fields: `x`, `y`, `density`). Materials have NO name/formula field -- they are anonymous data points.\n\nKey problems confirmed through code inspection:\n\n1. **Dead imports** (lines 9-11): `EffectComposer.js`, `RenderPass.js`, and `UnrealBloomPass.js` are loaded but never referenced anywhere in the 420 lines of JavaScript.\n2. **Spread operator on 21K arrays** (lines 504-505): `Math.min(...data.materials.map(m => m.x))` creates a 21,263-element temporary array and spreads it as function arguments. This hits call stack limits on some engines and is O(4n) where O(n) suffices.\n3. **No axis labels**: The `AxesHelper` at line 472 draws colored lines but has zero text labels. Scientists see colored sticks with no \"PCA Component 1\" or \"Tc (K)\" labels.\n4. **Sparse boxes at opacity 0.08** (line 595): Pulsing between 0.06 and 0.10 (line 766) -- effectively invisible against the dark background.\n5. **Mobile breakpoint is broken** (lines 330-335): Sets all panels to `position: relative` which stacks them on top of the 3D canvas instead of overlaying it. The canvas itself has no responsive handling.\n6. **No entry animation**: Data appears instantly when the fetch resolves. No camera sweep, no staggered reveal.\n7. **No bloom**: The biggest wasted opportunity. The imports are there, the additive blending is there, the dark background is perfect for it.\n8. **Missing CDN dependency**: UnrealBloomPass in Three.js r128 requires `ShaderPass.js`, `CopyShader.js`, and `LuminosityHighPassShader.js`. These are NOT included in the current `<script>` tags. Even if the code tried to use bloom, it would crash.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture Decisions\n\n### 2.1 File Budget\n\nCurrent file: 28.8 KB. Target: under 50 KB. That gives approximately 21 KB of headroom. Given that CSS is already ~5.5 KB and HTML ~2 KB, the JavaScript section can grow from ~14 KB to approximately ~35 KB. This is tight but workable for everything below.\n\n### 2.2 Module Pattern Within Single File\n\nThe current code dumps everything in global scope. Refactor into an IIFE with a clear namespace pattern:\n\n```javascript\n(function SuperSearch() {\n    // --- CONFIG ---\n    const CONFIG = { ... };\n    \n    // --- STATE ---\n    const state = { materials: [], clusterVisibility: [true,true,true], ... };\n    \n    // --- SCENE SETUP ---\n    function initScene() { ... }\n    \n    // --- DATA LOADING ---\n    function loadData() { ... }\n    \n    // --- VISUALIZATION ---\n    function createPoints(data) { ... }\n    function createSparseRegions(data) { ... }\n    function createAxisLabels() { ... }\n    \n    // --- POST-PROCESSING ---\n    function initBloom() { ... }\n    \n    // --- ANIMATION ---\n    function entryAnimation() { ... }\n    function animate() { ... }\n    \n    // --- INTERACTION ---\n    function initRaycasting() { ... }\n    function initTcSlider() { ... }\n    \n    // --- UI ---\n    function buildUI() { ... }\n    \n    // --- INIT ---\n    initScene();\n    loadData();\n})();\n```\n\nFunctions exposed to HTML `onclick` handlers must be attached to `window` explicitly: `window.setView = setView;`\n\n### 2.3 Data Stays External\n\nThe 3.2 MB JSON file stays external at `data/analysis_results.json`. Inlining it would blow past the 50 KB budget by 60x. The loading sequence must remain a fetch.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Implementation Plan -- Ordered by Priority\n\n### Phase 1: Fix What Is Broken (Effort: Low, Impact: Critical)\n\n#### 1A. Fix the Bloom Pipeline\n\n**Problem**: Three `<script>` tags load post-processing modules that are never used, and the dependency chain is incomplete.\n\n**Action**: Add missing CDN dependencies and wire up the EffectComposer.\n\nAdd these script tags after line 11:\n```html\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/CopyShader.js\"></script>\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/LuminosityHighPassShader.js\"></script>\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/postprocessing/ShaderPass.js\"></script>\n```\n\nThen in JavaScript, after the renderer setup (after line 439):\n```javascript\n// Post-processing: Bloom\nconst composer = new THREE.EffectComposer(renderer);\nconst renderPass = new THREE.RenderPass(scene, camera);\ncomposer.addPass(renderPass);\n\nconst bloomPass = new THREE.UnrealBloomPass(\n    new THREE.Vector2(container.clientWidth, container.clientHeight),\n    0.8,    // strength -- subtle, not overwhelming\n    0.4,    // radius\n    0.85    // threshold -- only bright particles bloom\n);\ncomposer.addPass(bloomPass);\n```\n\nIn the animate loop (line 770), replace `renderer.render(scene, camera)` with `composer.render()`.\n\nIn the resize handler (line 778), add `composer.setSize(w, h)`.\n\n**Tuning notes**: Strength of 0.8 with threshold 0.85 means only the brightest particles (high-Tc, white-hot center of sprites) get the glow halo. This creates a natural visual hierarchy where high-Tc materials literally glow.\n\n#### 1B. Fix Extent Calculation Performance\n\n**Problem**: Lines 504-505 create four 21K-element arrays via `.map()` then spread them as arguments to `Math.min/max`. This is O(4n) allocations and risks stack overflow.\n\n**Replace with** a single-pass reduce:\n```javascript\nlet xMin = Infinity, xMax = -Infinity, yMin = Infinity, yMax = -Infinity;\nfor (let i = 0; i < data.materials.length; i++) {\n    const m = data.materials[i];\n    if (m.x < xMin) xMin = m.x;\n    if (m.x > xMax) xMax = m.x;\n    if (m.y < yMin) yMin = m.y;\n    if (m.y > yMax) yMax = m.y;\n}\nconst xExtent = [xMin, xMax];\nconst yExtent = [yMin, yMax];\n```\n\nThis is O(n) with zero allocations. On 21K points the difference is negligible in wall time but it demonstrates competence.\n\n#### 1C. Fix Mobile Responsive\n\n**Problem**: The media query at line 330 sets panels to `position: relative`, which breaks the overlay layout entirely.\n\n**Replace with**:\n```css\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n    #header { top: 16px; left: 16px; }\n    #controls { top: 16px; right: 16px; min-width: 180px; padding: 16px; }\n    #stats { bottom: 16px; left: 16px; font-size: 0.75rem; }\n    #legend { bottom: 16px; right: 16px; padding: 16px; }\n    h1 { font-size: 1.1rem; }\n    .button-group { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }\n    .instructions { display: none; }\n}\n@media (max-width: 480px) {\n    #controls { display: none; }\n    #stats { display: none; }\n}\n```\n\nThis keeps panels overlaid on the 3D canvas at smaller sizes, hides lower-priority UI on very small screens, and never breaks the fullscreen canvas layout.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2: Visual Impact -- The \"Wow\" Factor (Effort: Medium, Impact: Highest)\n\n#### 2A. Entry Animation: Camera Sweep + Staggered Particle Reveal\n\nThis is the single highest-impact change for first impressions.\n\n**Concept**: When data loads, the camera starts at a dramatic angle looking at an empty scene. Particles materialize in waves (by cluster, then sparse regions pulse in). Camera sweeps from a cinematic angle to the default overview position.\n\n**Implementation approach**:\n\n1. Start particles with size = 0 using a custom `size` attribute on the BufferGeometry (already stored at line 564).\n2. On data load, animate sizes from 0 to their target values over 2 seconds using an easing function, staggered by cluster (Family A first at t=0, Family B at t=0.3s, Family C at t=0.6s).\n3. Simultaneously animate the camera from `(0, 120, 0)` (dramatic overhead) along a bezier curve to `(80, 60, 80)` (the default overview).\n\n```javascript\nfunction entryAnimation() {\n    const startTime = performance.now();\n    const duration = 2500; // ms\n    const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n    const targetSizes = new Float32Array(sizes.array); // copy targets\n    \n    // Zero out all sizes initially\n    sizes.array.fill(0);\n    sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n    \n    // Camera start position (dramatic top-down)\n    camera.position.set(0, 150, 0);\n    controls.target.set(0, 0, 0);\n    \n    function step() {\n        const elapsed = performance.now() - startTime;\n        const t = Math.min(elapsed / duration, 1);\n        \n        // Camera sweep: top-down to overview via smooth interpolation\n        const camT = easeOutCubic(t);\n        camera.position.set(\n            80 * camT,\n            150 - 90 * camT,\n            80 * camT\n        );\n        \n        // Staggered particle reveal by cluster\n        for (let i = 0; i < materials.length; i++) {\n            const cluster = materials[i].cluster;\n            const delay = cluster * 0.12; // 0, 0.12, 0.24\n            const localT = Math.max(0, Math.min((t - delay) / (1 - delay), 1));\n            sizes.array[i] = targetSizes[i] * easeOutBack(localT);\n        }\n        sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        if (t < 1) requestAnimationFrame(step);\n        else controls.autoRotate = true;\n    }\n    step();\n}\n\nfunction easeOutCubic(t) { return 1 - Math.pow(1 - t, 3); }\nfunction easeOutBack(t) { \n    const c = 1.70158; \n    return 1 + (c + 1) * Math.pow(t - 1, 3) + c * Math.pow(t - 1, 2); \n}\n```\n\nThis creates the \"wow\" effect: particles bloom outward from nothing, family by family, while the camera sweeps down from overhead. The `easeOutBack` gives a subtle overshoot that makes particles feel like they're \"popping\" into existence.\n\n#### 2B. Glow Halos for High-Tc Materials\n\n**Problem**: All 21K points look the same size-wise. High-Tc materials (the scientifically interesting ones) don't stand out.\n\n**Approach**: Use a second Points layer with larger, more transparent sprites for materials with Tc > 100K.\n\n```javascript\n// After creating the main pointsMesh\nconst glowIndices = [];\nconst glowPositions = [];\nconst glowColors = [];\nconst glowSizes = [];\n\nmaterials.forEach((m, i) => {\n    if (m.tc > 100) {\n        glowPositions.push(positions[i*3], positions[i*3+1], positions[i*3+2]);\n        glowColors.push(colors[i*3], colors[i*3+1], colors[i*3+2]);\n        glowSizes.push(sizes[i] * 4); // 4x larger halo\n    }\n});\n\nconst glowGeometry = new THREE.BufferGeometry();\nglowGeometry.setAttribute('position', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(glowPositions, 3));\nglowGeometry.setAttribute('color', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(glowColors, 3));\n\nconst glowMaterial = new THREE.PointsMaterial({\n    size: 5,\n    vertexColors: true,\n    transparent: true,\n    opacity: 0.15,\n    map: sprite,\n    blending: THREE.AdditiveBlending,\n    depthWrite: false\n});\n\nconst glowMesh = new THREE.Points(glowGeometry, glowMaterial);\nscene.add(glowMesh);\n```\n\nCombined with the UnrealBloomPass, this creates a double-glow effect: the bloom post-processing adds a screen-space glow, while the second particle layer adds an in-scene volumetric feel. The ~1,423 high-Tc points will have visible halos while the 20K ordinary points stay clean.\n\n#### 2C. Make Sparse Regions Compelling\n\n**Problem**: Opacity 0.08 is invisible. The \"opportunity zones\" -- the most scientifically actionable part of the visualization -- are the hardest to see.\n\n**New approach**: Replace solid boxes with animated wireframe columns that pulse with a \"scanning\" effect.\n\n```javascript\ndata.sparse_regions.forEach((region, index) => {\n    const centerX = xScale(region.x);\n    const centerZ = yScale(region.y);\n    \n    // Wireframe-only column (no solid fill -- cleaner look)\n    const boxGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(gridSize * 2, scaleZ * 0.6, gridSize * 2);\n    const edges = new THREE.EdgesGeometry(boxGeometry);\n    const lineMaterial = new THREE.LineBasicMaterial({\n        color: 0x22d3ee, // Cyan -- distinct from cluster colors\n        transparent: true,\n        opacity: 0.6\n    });\n    const wireframe = new THREE.LineSegments(edges, lineMaterial);\n    wireframe.position.set(centerX, 0, centerZ);\n    scene.add(wireframe);\n    \n    // Scanning plane that moves vertically inside the box\n    const planeGeometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(gridSize * 2, gridSize * 2);\n    const planeMaterial = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({\n        color: 0x22d3ee,\n        transparent: true,\n        opacity: 0.12,\n        side: THREE.DoubleSide\n    });\n    const scanPlane = new THREE.Mesh(planeGeometry, planeMaterial);\n    scanPlane.rotation.x = Math.PI / 2;\n    scanPlane.position.set(centerX, 0, centerZ);\n    scene.add(scanPlane);\n    \n    sparseBoxes.push({ wireframe, scanPlane, baseY: 0, height: scaleZ * 0.6 });\n});\n```\n\nIn the animation loop, animate the scanning plane:\n```javascript\nsparseBoxes.forEach((box, i) => {\n    const t = (Date.now() * 0.0005 + i * 0.3) % 1;\n    box.scanPlane.position.y = box.baseY - box.height/2 + t * box.height;\n    box.wireframe.material.opacity = 0.4 + Math.sin(Date.now() * 0.002 + i) * 0.2;\n});\n```\n\nThe cyan color distinguishes sparse regions from the blue/purple/pink cluster palette. The scanning plane animation suggests \"these are areas being investigated\" -- resonant for the autonomous lab narrative.\n\n#### 2D. Background Stars / Ambient Particles\n\nAdd a subtle star field behind the data to create depth and atmosphere.\n\n```javascript\nconst starGeometry = new THREE.BufferGeometry();\nconst starPositions = new Float32Array(1000 * 3);\nfor (let i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {\n    starPositions[i * 3] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n    starPositions[i * 3 + 1] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n    starPositions[i * 3 + 2] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n}\nstarGeometry.setAttribute('position', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(starPositions, 3));\n\nconst starMaterial = new THREE.PointsMaterial({\n    size: 0.3,\n    color: 0x334155,\n    transparent: true,\n    opacity: 0.5\n});\nscene.add(new THREE.Points(starGeometry, starMaterial));\n```\n\nThis is 1,000 tiny dim points in a large sphere around the data. They provide parallax depth during orbit and make the scene feel like a \"data universe\" rather than data floating in a void.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3: Scientific Communication (Effort: Medium, Impact: High)\n\n#### 3A. 3D Axis Labels Using Canvas-Based Text Sprites\n\nCSS2DRenderer requires an additional CDN dependency and creates DOM elements that interact poorly with post-processing. Canvas-based text sprites are self-contained and render through the bloom pipeline (text can glow subtly).\n\n```javascript\nfunction createTextSprite(text, color = '#888888', fontSize = 48) {\n    const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');\n    canvas.width = 512;\n    canvas.height = 64;\n    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');\n    ctx.font = `${fontSize}px Inter, sans-serif`;\n    ctx.fillStyle = color;\n    ctx.textAlign = 'center';\n    ctx.textBaseline = 'middle';\n    ctx.fillText(text, 256, 32);\n    \n    const texture = new THREE.CanvasTexture(canvas);\n    const spriteMaterial = new THREE.SpriteMaterial({ \n        map: texture, \n        transparent: true,\n        depthTest: false\n    });\n    const sprite = new THREE.Sprite(spriteMaterial);\n    sprite.scale.set(20, 2.5, 1);\n    return sprite;\n}\n\n// X axis label\nconst xLabel = createTextSprite('PCA Component 1 (Composition)');\nxLabel.position.set(0, -42, -35);\nscene.add(xLabel);\n\n// Z axis label (mapped from PCA y)\nconst zLabel = createTextSprite('PCA Component 2 (Composition)');\nzLabel.position.set(-35, -42, 0);\nscene.add(zLabel);\n\n// Y axis label (Tc)\nconst yLabel = createTextSprite('Critical Temperature Tc (K)', '#60a5fa');\nyLabel.position.set(-35, 0, -35);\nscene.add(yLabel);\n\n// Tc tick marks at key temperatures\n[0, 50, 100, 150, 185].forEach(tc => {\n    const y = zScale(tc);\n    const tick = createTextSprite(`${tc}K`, '#666666', 36);\n    tick.position.set(-34, y, -34);\n    tick.scale.set(10, 1.25, 1);\n    scene.add(tick);\n});\n```\n\n**Why sprites over CSS2D**: Sprites participate in the scene's depth and bloom. They feel integrated rather than overlaid. They also do not require additional CDN imports.\n\n#### 3B. PCA Variance Annotation\n\nAdd a small annotation in the header subtitle explaining what PCA axes mean:\n\nIn the HTML, change the subtitle from a static string to include variance:\n```html\n<div class=\"subtitle\">\n    21,263 superconductors in composition space \n    <span style=\"color:#555\">(PCA: 73.5% variance retained)</span>\n</div>\n```\n\nAdd axis variance to the stats panel:\n```html\n<div><span class=\"stat-label\">PC1 Variance:</span> <span class=\"stat-value\">54.2%</span></div>\n<div><span class=\"stat-label\">PC2 Variance:</span> <span class=\"stat-value\">19.3%</span></div>\n```\n\n(These exact values come from `data.metadata.pca_variance.pc1` and `pc2` in the JSON.)\n\n#### 3C. Better Cluster Names\n\nReplace \"Family A/B/C\" with scientifically meaningful names. Based on the data analysis in `analyze_data.py`, the PCA is over `mean_atomic_mass`, `mean_atomic_radius`, `mean_Valence`, `mean_fie`, `mean_Density`. The three DBSCAN clusters represent compositional groupings.\n\nReplace the legend labels:\n```javascript\nconst clusterNames = [\n    'Heavy-atom Compounds',    // Cluster 0 -- likely high atomic mass (cuprates)\n    'Light Intermetallics',    // Cluster 1 -- likely light elements, small radius\n    'Mixed-valence Systems'    // Cluster 2 -- likely variable valence\n];\n```\n\n**Important caveat**: These names should ideally be derived from inspecting the PCA loadings. Since the JSON does not include PCA loadings, the implementer should either: (a) add loadings to the JSON from `analyze_data.py` (`pca.components_`), or (b) use the generic but more accurate names \"Composition Family 1 (n=X)\" with a tooltip explaining the dominant features. For the initial implementation, option (b) is safer.\n\n#### 3D. Sparse Region Tooltip Annotations\n\nWhen hovering near a sparse region, show a tooltip with the region's density score and a message like \"Under-explored: only N materials in this grid cell.\"\n\nThis requires extending the raycasting to check proximity to sparse region positions:\n```javascript\n// In the mousemove handler, after checking point intersections:\nif (intersects.length === 0) {\n    // Check if mouse is near a sparse region\n    sparseRegions.forEach((region, i) => {\n        const screenPos = toScreenPosition(region.worldPos, camera, renderer);\n        const dist = Math.hypot(event.clientX - screenPos.x, event.clientY - screenPos.y);\n        if (dist < 30) {\n            showSparseTooltip(region, event);\n        }\n    });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4: Interactive Features (Effort: Medium-High, Impact: High)\n\n#### 4A. Tc Range Slider (Dual-Handle)\n\nThis is the most impactful interactive feature. Scientists want to isolate Tc ranges.\n\n**Implementation**: Pure CSS/JS dual-range slider (no library needed).\n\nHTML addition inside the `#controls` panel:\n```html\n<div class=\"control-group\">\n    <div class=\"control-label\">Tc Range (K)</div>\n    <div class=\"range-slider\">\n        <input type=\"range\" id=\"tc-min\" min=\"0\" max=\"185\" value=\"0\" step=\"1\">\n        <input type=\"range\" id=\"tc-max\" min=\"0\" max=\"185\" value=\"185\" step=\"1\">\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"range-values\">\n        <span id=\"tc-min-val\">0K</span>\n        <span id=\"tc-max-val\">185K</span>\n    </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nCSS for dual-range overlay:\n```css\n.range-slider {\n    position: relative;\n    height: 30px;\n}\n.range-slider input[type=\"range\"] {\n    position: absolute;\n    width: 100%;\n    -webkit-appearance: none;\n    background: transparent;\n    pointer-events: none;\n}\n.range-slider input[type=\"range\"]::-webkit-slider-thumb {\n    -webkit-appearance: none;\n    height: 16px;\n    width: 16px;\n    border-radius: 50%;\n    background: #3b82f6;\n    pointer-events: auto;\n    cursor: pointer;\n}\n```\n\nJavaScript handler:\n```javascript\nfunction filterByTc(min, max) {\n    const colors = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.color;\n    const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n    \n    materials.forEach((m, i) => {\n        const visible = m.tc >= min && m.tc <= max && clusterVisibility[m.cluster];\n        const color = clusterColors[m.cluster];\n        const alpha = visible ? 1 : 0.03;\n        colors.array[i * 3] = color.r * alpha;\n        colors.array[i * 3 + 1] = color.g * alpha;\n        colors.array[i * 3 + 2] = color.b * alpha;\n        sizes.array[i] = visible ? targetSizes[i] : 0.1;\n    });\n    \n    colors.needsUpdate = true;\n    sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n    \n    // Update visible count\n    const visibleCount = materials.filter(m => m.tc >= min && m.tc <= max).length;\n    document.getElementById('visible-count').textContent = visibleCount.toLocaleString();\n}\n```\n\nThe approach of dimming rather than removing filtered points preserves spatial context -- the scientist can still see where the hidden points were, just faintly.\n\n#### 4B. Click-to-Select with Detail Panel\n\nWhen a user clicks a point (not just hovers), pin the tooltip and show an expanded detail panel.\n\n```javascript\nlet selectedIndex = -1;\n\nrenderer.domElement.addEventListener('click', (event) => {\n    raycaster.setFromCamera(mouse, camera);\n    const intersects = raycaster.intersectObject(pointsMesh);\n    \n    if (intersects.length > 0) {\n        const index = intersects[0].index;\n        selectedIndex = index;\n        const m = materials[index];\n        \n        // Highlight selected point (increase size temporarily)\n        const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n        sizes.array[index] = targetSizes[index] * 3;\n        sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        // Show detail panel\n        showDetailPanel(m, index);\n    } else {\n        clearSelection();\n    }\n});\n```\n\nThe detail panel shows all available properties: `tc`, `atomic_mass`, `atomic_radius`, `valence`, `cluster`, plus the PCA coordinates. For a dataset without material names, the panel should show \"Material #N\" and the numeric properties formatted with units.\n\n#### 4C. Property-Based Search\n\nSince materials have no names, search is by property ranges. Add a collapsible \"Filter\" section:\n\n```html\n<div class=\"control-group\">\n    <div class=\"control-label\">Filter by Properties</div>\n    <div class=\"filter-row\">\n        <label>Atomic Mass</label>\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"mass-min\" placeholder=\"min\" step=\"0.1\">\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"mass-max\" placeholder=\"max\" step=\"0.1\">\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"filter-row\">\n        <label>Atomic Radius</label>\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"radius-min\" placeholder=\"min\" step=\"0.01\">\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"radius-max\" placeholder=\"max\" step=\"0.01\">\n    </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nThis applies the same color-dimming approach as the Tc slider but across multiple properties simultaneously.\n\n**Budget concern**: This adds ~40 lines of CSS and ~30 lines of JS. If file size is tight, this feature can be deferred in favor of the Tc slider alone, which covers 80% of the use case.\n\n#### 4D. Density Heatmap Toggle\n\n**Approach**: Create a second Points mesh that renders a grid of semi-transparent cubes colored by local density. Precompute a 20x20x20 grid of point counts during data load.\n\n**Decision**: This is the lowest-priority interactive feature. It adds visual complexity without proportional insight, and it competes with the sparse region visualization for visual attention. Recommend deferring unless file size allows. If implemented, make it a toggle that replaces the point cloud temporarily rather than overlaying it.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 5: Code Quality (Effort: Medium, Impact: Professional Impression)\n\n#### 5A. IIFE Wrapper + CONFIG Object\n\nWrap all code in an IIFE as described in section 2.2. Extract magic numbers into a CONFIG object at the top:\n\n```javascript\nconst CONFIG = {\n    SCALE: { x: 60, y: 60, z: 60 },\n    CAMERA: { fov: 50, near: 0.1, far: 1000, default: [80, 60, 80] },\n    BLOOM: { strength: 0.8, radius: 0.4, threshold: 0.85 },\n    ANIMATION: { entryDuration: 2500, cameraDuration: 1000 },\n    GLOW_TC_THRESHOLD: 100,\n    SPARSE_COLOR: 0x22d3ee,\n    CLUSTER_COLORS: [0x3b82f6, 0x8b5cf6, 0xec4899],\n    STAR_COUNT: 1000,\n    RAYCASTER_THRESHOLD: 1\n};\n```\n\n#### 5B. Cache Computed Values\n\nStore `targetSizes` as a module-level Float32Array so the Tc slider and cluster toggle do not need to recompute them. Store `originalColors` similarly. Currently, `toggleCluster()` at line 685 recomputes `originalColors` on every call by mapping over all 21K materials.\n\n```javascript\n// Computed once after point creation:\nconst cachedState = {\n    targetSizes: null,    // Float32Array\n    originalColors: null, // Float32Array (r,g,b per point)\n    positions: null       // Float32Array (x,y,z per point)\n};\n```\n\n#### 5C. Better Error Handling\n\nThe current fetch error handler (line 497) just logs to console and shows a red error div. Add:\n- Retry logic (one retry after 2 seconds)\n- Specific error messages for network vs. JSON parse errors\n- Fallback to show a meaningful message if the data file is missing\n\n```javascript\nasync function loadData() {\n    for (let attempt = 0; attempt < 2; attempt++) {\n        try {\n            const response = await fetch('data/analysis_results.json');\n            if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n            const data = await response.json();\n            return data;\n        } catch (e) {\n            if (attempt === 0) {\n                updateLoadingText('Retrying...');\n                await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000));\n            } else {\n                showError(`Failed to load data: ${e.message}`);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 6: Polish (Effort: Low, Impact: Medium)\n\n#### 6A. Cinematic Loading Sequence\n\nReplace the basic spinner with a progress bar and staged messages:\n\n```javascript\nconst loadingMessages = [\n    'Initializing Three.js scene...',\n    'Loading 21,263 superconductors...',\n    'Computing spatial layout...',\n    'Activating bloom post-processing...',\n    'Ready.'\n];\n```\n\nEach message appears as the corresponding initialization step completes. The last message fades out as the entry animation begins.\n\n#### 6B. Smooth Transitions for All State Changes\n\nThe current `toggleCluster()` instantly changes colors. Add interpolation:\n\n```javascript\nfunction animateColorTransition(duration = 300) {\n    const startColors = new Float32Array(currentColors);\n    const startTime = performance.now();\n    \n    function step() {\n        const t = Math.min((performance.now() - startTime) / duration, 1);\n        const eased = easeOutCubic(t);\n        \n        for (let i = 0; i < startColors.length; i++) {\n            currentColors[i] = startColors[i] + (targetColors[i] - startColors[i]) * eased;\n        }\n        pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.color.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        if (t < 1) requestAnimationFrame(step);\n    }\n    step();\n}\n```\n\nApply this to cluster toggles, Tc range changes, and camera transitions.\n\n#### 6C. Meta Tags, Favicon, Open Graph\n\nAdd to `<head>`:\n```html\n<meta name=\"description\" content=\"Interactive 3D visualization of 21,263 superconductors mapped in composition space. Explore critical temperature patterns, composition families, and under-explored regions.\">\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"SuperSearch - Superconductor Composition Explorer\">\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"21,263 superconductors mapped in 3D. Find where the next breakthrough might be hiding.\">\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https://reubenrunacres.github.io/supersearch/preview.png\">\n<meta name=\"twitter:card\" content=\"summary_large_image\">\n<link rel=\"icon\" href=\"data:image/svg+xml,<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 100 100'><text y='.9em' font-size='90'>🔬</text></svg>\">\n```\n\nThe favicon uses an inline SVG data URI (no external file needed). The og:image requires a screenshot saved as `preview.png`.\n\n#### 6D. Keyboard Shortcut Overlay\n\nShow a floating overlay when the user presses `?`:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n    if (e.key === '?') toggleShortcutOverlay();\n    // ... existing shortcuts\n});\n```\n\nThe overlay is a simple `<div>` with `position: fixed` that lists all shortcuts. Style it with the existing glassmorphic panel CSS.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Implementation Sequencing\n\nThe recommended order balances \"ship something impressive fast\" with \"don't create technical debt\":\n\n| Step | Task | Lines Added | Cumulative Size | Impact |\n|------|------|-------------|-----------------|--------|\n| 1 | IIFE wrapper + CONFIG object | +30 | ~29.5 KB | Foundation |\n| 2 | Fix bloom pipeline (add missing CDNs + wire up) | +25 | ~30.2 KB | Huge visual |\n| 3 | Fix extent calculation | -4, +8 | ~30.3 KB | Performance |\n| 4 | Entry animation | +55 | ~31.8 KB | Wow factor |\n| 5 | High-Tc glow halos (second particle layer) | +30 | ~32.7 KB | Visual depth |\n| 6 | Background stars | +15 | ~33.2 KB | Atmosphere |\n| 7 | 3D axis labels (canvas sprites) | +50 | ~34.6 KB | Scientific cred |\n| 8 | Sparse region redesign (cyan wireframe + scan plane) | +40 | ~35.7 KB | Science + visual |\n| 9 | Tc range slider | +60 (CSS+JS+HTML) | ~37.4 KB | Interactivity |\n| 10 | Click-to-select detail panel | +50 | ~38.8 KB | Exploration |\n| 11 | PCA variance annotations | +10 | ~39.1 KB | Science |\n| 12 | Smooth transitions | +25 | ~39.8 KB | Polish |\n| 13 | Cinematic loading | +20 | ~40.4 KB | First impression |\n| 14 | Meta tags + favicon | +15 | ~40.8 KB | SEO/sharing |\n| 15 | Fix mobile responsive | +20 (CSS) | ~41.4 KB | Accessibility |\n| 16 | Keyboard overlay | +30 | ~42.3 KB | Polish |\n| 17 | Cached computed values | +15, -10 | ~42.4 KB | Performance |\n\n**Total estimated final size: ~42 KB** -- well within the 50 KB budget.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Risk Assessment\n\n**Risk 1: Bloom + 21K additive-blended points = washed-out white mess.**\nMitigation: Set bloom threshold to 0.85 so only the bright sprite centers bloom. Test with strength values 0.5-1.0. The fog at line 425 (`FogExp2` density 0.002) will attenuate distant points, preventing global blowout.\n\n**Risk 2: Entry animation conflicts with the existing `animate()` loop.**\nMitigation: The entry animation runs as a separate `requestAnimationFrame` loop that only modifies `sizes.array` and `camera.position`. The main `animate()` loop still handles rendering. Do NOT block the main loop.\n\n**Risk 3: Dual-range slider CSS is finicky cross-browser.**\nMitigation: Use the z-index stacking approach where both inputs overlap. Test on Chrome/Safari/Firefox. If Firefox styling is problematic, fall back to a single range input with a numeric min/max display.\n\n**Risk 4: Canvas text sprites look blurry at certain zoom levels.**\nMitigation: Use 512px wide canvas for text (already specified above). Set `sprite.scale` proportionally. The text will be crisp at the default zoom level and acceptable at 2x zoom. For very close zoom, the sprites can be made to face the camera with `sprite.material.sizeAttenuation = false` but this changes the aesthetic -- test before committing.\n\n**Risk 5: ShaderPass/CopyShader CDN files might not exist for r128.**\nMitigation: The Three.js examples directory for r128 on jsdelivr has been stable since 2021. The files exist at:\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/CopyShader.js`\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/LuminosityHighPassShader.js`\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/postprocessing/ShaderPass.js`\n\nVerify before deploying. If unavailable, inline the shader code (CopyShader is ~20 lines, LuminosityHighPassShader is ~40 lines).\n\n---\n\n## 6. What NOT to Do\n\n1. **Do not switch to ES modules / import maps.** Three.js r128 via CDN uses the global `THREE` namespace. The import-map approach requires r128+ module builds that have different CDN paths. Stay with the `<script>` tag approach.\n\n2. **Do not add GSAP or tween.js.** The entry animation and transitions are simple enough to implement with `requestAnimationFrame` + easing functions. Adding a 40KB animation library is not justified.\n\n3. **Do not add a search-by-name feature.** The data does not contain material names or formulas. The `material` field checked at line 733 (`material.material || 'Superconductor ' + index`) is undefined for all entries. To add names, the `analyze_data.py` pipeline would need to be modified to include the original formula from the CSV, which is a data pipeline change, not a frontend change.\n\n4. **Do not implement the density heatmap** unless all higher-priority items are done and there is size budget remaining. It is the lowest bang-for-buck feature on the list.\n\n5. **Do not use `CSS2DRenderer`** for axis labels. It adds a CDN dependency, creates DOM elements that don't participate in bloom, and requires a separate render pass.\n\n---\n\n### Critical Files for Implementation\n\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/docs/index.html` - The single self-contained visualization file that must be modified. All 795 lines of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript live here.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/data/analysis_results.json` - The 3.2 MB JSON data source. Understanding its schema (materials array with x/y/tc/cluster/atomic_mass/atomic_radius/valence, sparse_regions array with x/y/density, metadata with pca_variance/tc_range) is essential for every feature.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/analyze_data.py` - The Python pipeline that generates the JSON. Must be modified if better cluster names or material formulas are needed (it currently discards material identity).\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/web-original/index.html` - The original D3.js 2D version. Contains axis label patterns and insight text that should be ported to the 3D version for scientific completeness.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/FOR_PERIODIC_LABS.md` - The pitch document containing cluster descriptions (\"cuprate-like\", \"pnictide-inspired\", \"mixed-metal\") and strategic framing that should inform the visualization's annotations and naming."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a5306ed (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 55204\ntool_uses: 30\nduration_ms: 253688</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df77d6ed-acd7-4370-ab29-6b857b89c4cf","uuid":"385178e9-483e-4867-92d5-cffbb3274253","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a senior frontend engineer and data visualization specialist. Design a comprehensive implementation plan to upgrade a Three.js 3D superconductor visualization from \"good demo\" to \"wow, hire this person\" quality.\n\n## Current State\n- 795-line self-contained HTML file using Three.js r128\n- 21,263 superconductor points in 3D (PCA x, PCA y, Tc on vertical axis)\n- 3 cluster families (DBSCAN), 34 sparse regions\n- Basic orbit controls, tooltips, legend filtering, camera presets\n- Dark theme with glassmorphic UI panels\n\n## Critical Issues Found\n1. **Bloom post-processing imported but NEVER used** - dead code, worst kind of red flag\n2. **No axis labels at all** - scientists can't read the visualization\n3. **No entry animation** - data just appears\n4. **Performance**: spread operator on 21K arrays for extent calculation\n5. **Sparse regions nearly invisible** (opacity 0.08)\n6. **No Tc filtering** - can't explore by temperature range\n7. **No material search/selection**\n8. **Code quality**: global scope, no modularity, dead imports\n9. **Missing meta tags, favicon, social sharing**\n10. **Mobile responsive is broken**\n\n## Available Data Per Material\n- x, y (PCA coordinates), tc (critical temp), cluster (0-2)\n- atomic_mass, atomic_radius, valence\n\n## Constraints\n- Must remain a single self-contained HTML file\n- CDN dependencies only (Three.js r128)\n- Must render 21K points smoothly on M-series MacBook\n- Must create instant \"wow\" factor within 5 seconds\n- Target audience: PhD scientists from DeepMind/OpenAI\n\n## Design the implementation plan covering:\n\n### A. Visual Impact (highest priority)\n1. Implement UnrealBloomPass properly (already imported)\n2. Entry animation: staggered particle reveal with camera sweep\n3. Better particle rendering: glow halos for high-Tc materials\n4. Make sparse regions visually compelling (not invisible)\n5. Subtle ambient particle effects or background stars\n\n### B. Scientific Communication\n1. 3D axis labels (CSS2DRenderer or canvas-based text sprites)\n2. Explain PCA variance on axes\n3. Sparse region annotations/tooltips\n4. Better cluster naming (not just \"Family A/B/C\")\n\n### C. Interactive Features\n1. Tc range slider (dual-handle)\n2. Search by properties\n3. Click-to-select individual materials with detail panel\n4. Density heatmap toggle\n\n### D. Code Quality\n1. Fix performance (single-pass extent calculation)\n2. Remove or implement dead imports\n3. Cache computed values\n4. Better error handling\n\n### E. Polish\n1. Cinematic loading sequence\n2. Smooth transitions for all state changes\n3. Meta tags and favicon\n4. Keyboard shortcut overlay\n\nBe specific about implementation approach. Think about what can be done in a SINGLE self-contained HTML file without getting bloated. Prioritize impact vs effort. The file should stay under ~50KB.","agentId":"a5306ed","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good. I have now thoroughly explored the codebase. Let me compile the comprehensive implementation plan.\n\n---\n\n# SuperSearch Visualization Upgrade: Comprehensive Implementation Plan\n\n## 1. Current State Assessment\n\nThe file at `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/docs/index.html` is 795 lines, approximately 28.8 KB. It uses Three.js r128 via CDN, loads a 3.2 MB JSON file containing 21,263 material data points (fields: `x`, `y`, `tc`, `cluster`, `atomic_mass`, `atomic_radius`, `valence`) and 34 sparse regions (fields: `x`, `y`, `density`). Materials have NO name/formula field -- they are anonymous data points.\n\nKey problems confirmed through code inspection:\n\n1. **Dead imports** (lines 9-11): `EffectComposer.js`, `RenderPass.js`, and `UnrealBloomPass.js` are loaded but never referenced anywhere in the 420 lines of JavaScript.\n2. **Spread operator on 21K arrays** (lines 504-505): `Math.min(...data.materials.map(m => m.x))` creates a 21,263-element temporary array and spreads it as function arguments. This hits call stack limits on some engines and is O(4n) where O(n) suffices.\n3. **No axis labels**: The `AxesHelper` at line 472 draws colored lines but has zero text labels. Scientists see colored sticks with no \"PCA Component 1\" or \"Tc (K)\" labels.\n4. **Sparse boxes at opacity 0.08** (line 595): Pulsing between 0.06 and 0.10 (line 766) -- effectively invisible against the dark background.\n5. **Mobile breakpoint is broken** (lines 330-335): Sets all panels to `position: relative` which stacks them on top of the 3D canvas instead of overlaying it. The canvas itself has no responsive handling.\n6. **No entry animation**: Data appears instantly when the fetch resolves. No camera sweep, no staggered reveal.\n7. **No bloom**: The biggest wasted opportunity. The imports are there, the additive blending is there, the dark background is perfect for it.\n8. **Missing CDN dependency**: UnrealBloomPass in Three.js r128 requires `ShaderPass.js`, `CopyShader.js`, and `LuminosityHighPassShader.js`. These are NOT included in the current `<script>` tags. Even if the code tried to use bloom, it would crash.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture Decisions\n\n### 2.1 File Budget\n\nCurrent file: 28.8 KB. Target: under 50 KB. That gives approximately 21 KB of headroom. Given that CSS is already ~5.5 KB and HTML ~2 KB, the JavaScript section can grow from ~14 KB to approximately ~35 KB. This is tight but workable for everything below.\n\n### 2.2 Module Pattern Within Single File\n\nThe current code dumps everything in global scope. Refactor into an IIFE with a clear namespace pattern:\n\n```javascript\n(function SuperSearch() {\n    // --- CONFIG ---\n    const CONFIG = { ... };\n    \n    // --- STATE ---\n    const state = { materials: [], clusterVisibility: [true,true,true], ... };\n    \n    // --- SCENE SETUP ---\n    function initScene() { ... }\n    \n    // --- DATA LOADING ---\n    function loadData() { ... }\n    \n    // --- VISUALIZATION ---\n    function createPoints(data) { ... }\n    function createSparseRegions(data) { ... }\n    function createAxisLabels() { ... }\n    \n    // --- POST-PROCESSING ---\n    function initBloom() { ... }\n    \n    // --- ANIMATION ---\n    function entryAnimation() { ... }\n    function animate() { ... }\n    \n    // --- INTERACTION ---\n    function initRaycasting() { ... }\n    function initTcSlider() { ... }\n    \n    // --- UI ---\n    function buildUI() { ... }\n    \n    // --- INIT ---\n    initScene();\n    loadData();\n})();\n```\n\nFunctions exposed to HTML `onclick` handlers must be attached to `window` explicitly: `window.setView = setView;`\n\n### 2.3 Data Stays External\n\nThe 3.2 MB JSON file stays external at `data/analysis_results.json`. Inlining it would blow past the 50 KB budget by 60x. The loading sequence must remain a fetch.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Implementation Plan -- Ordered by Priority\n\n### Phase 1: Fix What Is Broken (Effort: Low, Impact: Critical)\n\n#### 1A. Fix the Bloom Pipeline\n\n**Problem**: Three `<script>` tags load post-processing modules that are never used, and the dependency chain is incomplete.\n\n**Action**: Add missing CDN dependencies and wire up the EffectComposer.\n\nAdd these script tags after line 11:\n```html\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/CopyShader.js\"></script>\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/LuminosityHighPassShader.js\"></script>\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/postprocessing/ShaderPass.js\"></script>\n```\n\nThen in JavaScript, after the renderer setup (after line 439):\n```javascript\n// Post-processing: Bloom\nconst composer = new THREE.EffectComposer(renderer);\nconst renderPass = new THREE.RenderPass(scene, camera);\ncomposer.addPass(renderPass);\n\nconst bloomPass = new THREE.UnrealBloomPass(\n    new THREE.Vector2(container.clientWidth, container.clientHeight),\n    0.8,    // strength -- subtle, not overwhelming\n    0.4,    // radius\n    0.85    // threshold -- only bright particles bloom\n);\ncomposer.addPass(bloomPass);\n```\n\nIn the animate loop (line 770), replace `renderer.render(scene, camera)` with `composer.render()`.\n\nIn the resize handler (line 778), add `composer.setSize(w, h)`.\n\n**Tuning notes**: Strength of 0.8 with threshold 0.85 means only the brightest particles (high-Tc, white-hot center of sprites) get the glow halo. This creates a natural visual hierarchy where high-Tc materials literally glow.\n\n#### 1B. Fix Extent Calculation Performance\n\n**Problem**: Lines 504-505 create four 21K-element arrays via `.map()` then spread them as arguments to `Math.min/max`. This is O(4n) allocations and risks stack overflow.\n\n**Replace with** a single-pass reduce:\n```javascript\nlet xMin = Infinity, xMax = -Infinity, yMin = Infinity, yMax = -Infinity;\nfor (let i = 0; i < data.materials.length; i++) {\n    const m = data.materials[i];\n    if (m.x < xMin) xMin = m.x;\n    if (m.x > xMax) xMax = m.x;\n    if (m.y < yMin) yMin = m.y;\n    if (m.y > yMax) yMax = m.y;\n}\nconst xExtent = [xMin, xMax];\nconst yExtent = [yMin, yMax];\n```\n\nThis is O(n) with zero allocations. On 21K points the difference is negligible in wall time but it demonstrates competence.\n\n#### 1C. Fix Mobile Responsive\n\n**Problem**: The media query at line 330 sets panels to `position: relative`, which breaks the overlay layout entirely.\n\n**Replace with**:\n```css\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n    #header { top: 16px; left: 16px; }\n    #controls { top: 16px; right: 16px; min-width: 180px; padding: 16px; }\n    #stats { bottom: 16px; left: 16px; font-size: 0.75rem; }\n    #legend { bottom: 16px; right: 16px; padding: 16px; }\n    h1 { font-size: 1.1rem; }\n    .button-group { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }\n    .instructions { display: none; }\n}\n@media (max-width: 480px) {\n    #controls { display: none; }\n    #stats { display: none; }\n}\n```\n\nThis keeps panels overlaid on the 3D canvas at smaller sizes, hides lower-priority UI on very small screens, and never breaks the fullscreen canvas layout.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2: Visual Impact -- The \"Wow\" Factor (Effort: Medium, Impact: Highest)\n\n#### 2A. Entry Animation: Camera Sweep + Staggered Particle Reveal\n\nThis is the single highest-impact change for first impressions.\n\n**Concept**: When data loads, the camera starts at a dramatic angle looking at an empty scene. Particles materialize in waves (by cluster, then sparse regions pulse in). Camera sweeps from a cinematic angle to the default overview position.\n\n**Implementation approach**:\n\n1. Start particles with size = 0 using a custom `size` attribute on the BufferGeometry (already stored at line 564).\n2. On data load, animate sizes from 0 to their target values over 2 seconds using an easing function, staggered by cluster (Family A first at t=0, Family B at t=0.3s, Family C at t=0.6s).\n3. Simultaneously animate the camera from `(0, 120, 0)` (dramatic overhead) along a bezier curve to `(80, 60, 80)` (the default overview).\n\n```javascript\nfunction entryAnimation() {\n    const startTime = performance.now();\n    const duration = 2500; // ms\n    const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n    const targetSizes = new Float32Array(sizes.array); // copy targets\n    \n    // Zero out all sizes initially\n    sizes.array.fill(0);\n    sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n    \n    // Camera start position (dramatic top-down)\n    camera.position.set(0, 150, 0);\n    controls.target.set(0, 0, 0);\n    \n    function step() {\n        const elapsed = performance.now() - startTime;\n        const t = Math.min(elapsed / duration, 1);\n        \n        // Camera sweep: top-down to overview via smooth interpolation\n        const camT = easeOutCubic(t);\n        camera.position.set(\n            80 * camT,\n            150 - 90 * camT,\n            80 * camT\n        );\n        \n        // Staggered particle reveal by cluster\n        for (let i = 0; i < materials.length; i++) {\n            const cluster = materials[i].cluster;\n            const delay = cluster * 0.12; // 0, 0.12, 0.24\n            const localT = Math.max(0, Math.min((t - delay) / (1 - delay), 1));\n            sizes.array[i] = targetSizes[i] * easeOutBack(localT);\n        }\n        sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        if (t < 1) requestAnimationFrame(step);\n        else controls.autoRotate = true;\n    }\n    step();\n}\n\nfunction easeOutCubic(t) { return 1 - Math.pow(1 - t, 3); }\nfunction easeOutBack(t) { \n    const c = 1.70158; \n    return 1 + (c + 1) * Math.pow(t - 1, 3) + c * Math.pow(t - 1, 2); \n}\n```\n\nThis creates the \"wow\" effect: particles bloom outward from nothing, family by family, while the camera sweeps down from overhead. The `easeOutBack` gives a subtle overshoot that makes particles feel like they're \"popping\" into existence.\n\n#### 2B. Glow Halos for High-Tc Materials\n\n**Problem**: All 21K points look the same size-wise. High-Tc materials (the scientifically interesting ones) don't stand out.\n\n**Approach**: Use a second Points layer with larger, more transparent sprites for materials with Tc > 100K.\n\n```javascript\n// After creating the main pointsMesh\nconst glowIndices = [];\nconst glowPositions = [];\nconst glowColors = [];\nconst glowSizes = [];\n\nmaterials.forEach((m, i) => {\n    if (m.tc > 100) {\n        glowPositions.push(positions[i*3], positions[i*3+1], positions[i*3+2]);\n        glowColors.push(colors[i*3], colors[i*3+1], colors[i*3+2]);\n        glowSizes.push(sizes[i] * 4); // 4x larger halo\n    }\n});\n\nconst glowGeometry = new THREE.BufferGeometry();\nglowGeometry.setAttribute('position', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(glowPositions, 3));\nglowGeometry.setAttribute('color', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(glowColors, 3));\n\nconst glowMaterial = new THREE.PointsMaterial({\n    size: 5,\n    vertexColors: true,\n    transparent: true,\n    opacity: 0.15,\n    map: sprite,\n    blending: THREE.AdditiveBlending,\n    depthWrite: false\n});\n\nconst glowMesh = new THREE.Points(glowGeometry, glowMaterial);\nscene.add(glowMesh);\n```\n\nCombined with the UnrealBloomPass, this creates a double-glow effect: the bloom post-processing adds a screen-space glow, while the second particle layer adds an in-scene volumetric feel. The ~1,423 high-Tc points will have visible halos while the 20K ordinary points stay clean.\n\n#### 2C. Make Sparse Regions Compelling\n\n**Problem**: Opacity 0.08 is invisible. The \"opportunity zones\" -- the most scientifically actionable part of the visualization -- are the hardest to see.\n\n**New approach**: Replace solid boxes with animated wireframe columns that pulse with a \"scanning\" effect.\n\n```javascript\ndata.sparse_regions.forEach((region, index) => {\n    const centerX = xScale(region.x);\n    const centerZ = yScale(region.y);\n    \n    // Wireframe-only column (no solid fill -- cleaner look)\n    const boxGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(gridSize * 2, scaleZ * 0.6, gridSize * 2);\n    const edges = new THREE.EdgesGeometry(boxGeometry);\n    const lineMaterial = new THREE.LineBasicMaterial({\n        color: 0x22d3ee, // Cyan -- distinct from cluster colors\n        transparent: true,\n        opacity: 0.6\n    });\n    const wireframe = new THREE.LineSegments(edges, lineMaterial);\n    wireframe.position.set(centerX, 0, centerZ);\n    scene.add(wireframe);\n    \n    // Scanning plane that moves vertically inside the box\n    const planeGeometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(gridSize * 2, gridSize * 2);\n    const planeMaterial = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({\n        color: 0x22d3ee,\n        transparent: true,\n        opacity: 0.12,\n        side: THREE.DoubleSide\n    });\n    const scanPlane = new THREE.Mesh(planeGeometry, planeMaterial);\n    scanPlane.rotation.x = Math.PI / 2;\n    scanPlane.position.set(centerX, 0, centerZ);\n    scene.add(scanPlane);\n    \n    sparseBoxes.push({ wireframe, scanPlane, baseY: 0, height: scaleZ * 0.6 });\n});\n```\n\nIn the animation loop, animate the scanning plane:\n```javascript\nsparseBoxes.forEach((box, i) => {\n    const t = (Date.now() * 0.0005 + i * 0.3) % 1;\n    box.scanPlane.position.y = box.baseY - box.height/2 + t * box.height;\n    box.wireframe.material.opacity = 0.4 + Math.sin(Date.now() * 0.002 + i) * 0.2;\n});\n```\n\nThe cyan color distinguishes sparse regions from the blue/purple/pink cluster palette. The scanning plane animation suggests \"these are areas being investigated\" -- resonant for the autonomous lab narrative.\n\n#### 2D. Background Stars / Ambient Particles\n\nAdd a subtle star field behind the data to create depth and atmosphere.\n\n```javascript\nconst starGeometry = new THREE.BufferGeometry();\nconst starPositions = new Float32Array(1000 * 3);\nfor (let i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {\n    starPositions[i * 3] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n    starPositions[i * 3 + 1] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n    starPositions[i * 3 + 2] = (Math.random() - 0.5) * 400;\n}\nstarGeometry.setAttribute('position', new THREE.Float32BufferAttribute(starPositions, 3));\n\nconst starMaterial = new THREE.PointsMaterial({\n    size: 0.3,\n    color: 0x334155,\n    transparent: true,\n    opacity: 0.5\n});\nscene.add(new THREE.Points(starGeometry, starMaterial));\n```\n\nThis is 1,000 tiny dim points in a large sphere around the data. They provide parallax depth during orbit and make the scene feel like a \"data universe\" rather than data floating in a void.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3: Scientific Communication (Effort: Medium, Impact: High)\n\n#### 3A. 3D Axis Labels Using Canvas-Based Text Sprites\n\nCSS2DRenderer requires an additional CDN dependency and creates DOM elements that interact poorly with post-processing. Canvas-based text sprites are self-contained and render through the bloom pipeline (text can glow subtly).\n\n```javascript\nfunction createTextSprite(text, color = '#888888', fontSize = 48) {\n    const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');\n    canvas.width = 512;\n    canvas.height = 64;\n    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');\n    ctx.font = `${fontSize}px Inter, sans-serif`;\n    ctx.fillStyle = color;\n    ctx.textAlign = 'center';\n    ctx.textBaseline = 'middle';\n    ctx.fillText(text, 256, 32);\n    \n    const texture = new THREE.CanvasTexture(canvas);\n    const spriteMaterial = new THREE.SpriteMaterial({ \n        map: texture, \n        transparent: true,\n        depthTest: false\n    });\n    const sprite = new THREE.Sprite(spriteMaterial);\n    sprite.scale.set(20, 2.5, 1);\n    return sprite;\n}\n\n// X axis label\nconst xLabel = createTextSprite('PCA Component 1 (Composition)');\nxLabel.position.set(0, -42, -35);\nscene.add(xLabel);\n\n// Z axis label (mapped from PCA y)\nconst zLabel = createTextSprite('PCA Component 2 (Composition)');\nzLabel.position.set(-35, -42, 0);\nscene.add(zLabel);\n\n// Y axis label (Tc)\nconst yLabel = createTextSprite('Critical Temperature Tc (K)', '#60a5fa');\nyLabel.position.set(-35, 0, -35);\nscene.add(yLabel);\n\n// Tc tick marks at key temperatures\n[0, 50, 100, 150, 185].forEach(tc => {\n    const y = zScale(tc);\n    const tick = createTextSprite(`${tc}K`, '#666666', 36);\n    tick.position.set(-34, y, -34);\n    tick.scale.set(10, 1.25, 1);\n    scene.add(tick);\n});\n```\n\n**Why sprites over CSS2D**: Sprites participate in the scene's depth and bloom. They feel integrated rather than overlaid. They also do not require additional CDN imports.\n\n#### 3B. PCA Variance Annotation\n\nAdd a small annotation in the header subtitle explaining what PCA axes mean:\n\nIn the HTML, change the subtitle from a static string to include variance:\n```html\n<div class=\"subtitle\">\n    21,263 superconductors in composition space \n    <span style=\"color:#555\">(PCA: 73.5% variance retained)</span>\n</div>\n```\n\nAdd axis variance to the stats panel:\n```html\n<div><span class=\"stat-label\">PC1 Variance:</span> <span class=\"stat-value\">54.2%</span></div>\n<div><span class=\"stat-label\">PC2 Variance:</span> <span class=\"stat-value\">19.3%</span></div>\n```\n\n(These exact values come from `data.metadata.pca_variance.pc1` and `pc2` in the JSON.)\n\n#### 3C. Better Cluster Names\n\nReplace \"Family A/B/C\" with scientifically meaningful names. Based on the data analysis in `analyze_data.py`, the PCA is over `mean_atomic_mass`, `mean_atomic_radius`, `mean_Valence`, `mean_fie`, `mean_Density`. The three DBSCAN clusters represent compositional groupings.\n\nReplace the legend labels:\n```javascript\nconst clusterNames = [\n    'Heavy-atom Compounds',    // Cluster 0 -- likely high atomic mass (cuprates)\n    'Light Intermetallics',    // Cluster 1 -- likely light elements, small radius\n    'Mixed-valence Systems'    // Cluster 2 -- likely variable valence\n];\n```\n\n**Important caveat**: These names should ideally be derived from inspecting the PCA loadings. Since the JSON does not include PCA loadings, the implementer should either: (a) add loadings to the JSON from `analyze_data.py` (`pca.components_`), or (b) use the generic but more accurate names \"Composition Family 1 (n=X)\" with a tooltip explaining the dominant features. For the initial implementation, option (b) is safer.\n\n#### 3D. Sparse Region Tooltip Annotations\n\nWhen hovering near a sparse region, show a tooltip with the region's density score and a message like \"Under-explored: only N materials in this grid cell.\"\n\nThis requires extending the raycasting to check proximity to sparse region positions:\n```javascript\n// In the mousemove handler, after checking point intersections:\nif (intersects.length === 0) {\n    // Check if mouse is near a sparse region\n    sparseRegions.forEach((region, i) => {\n        const screenPos = toScreenPosition(region.worldPos, camera, renderer);\n        const dist = Math.hypot(event.clientX - screenPos.x, event.clientY - screenPos.y);\n        if (dist < 30) {\n            showSparseTooltip(region, event);\n        }\n    });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4: Interactive Features (Effort: Medium-High, Impact: High)\n\n#### 4A. Tc Range Slider (Dual-Handle)\n\nThis is the most impactful interactive feature. Scientists want to isolate Tc ranges.\n\n**Implementation**: Pure CSS/JS dual-range slider (no library needed).\n\nHTML addition inside the `#controls` panel:\n```html\n<div class=\"control-group\">\n    <div class=\"control-label\">Tc Range (K)</div>\n    <div class=\"range-slider\">\n        <input type=\"range\" id=\"tc-min\" min=\"0\" max=\"185\" value=\"0\" step=\"1\">\n        <input type=\"range\" id=\"tc-max\" min=\"0\" max=\"185\" value=\"185\" step=\"1\">\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"range-values\">\n        <span id=\"tc-min-val\">0K</span>\n        <span id=\"tc-max-val\">185K</span>\n    </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nCSS for dual-range overlay:\n```css\n.range-slider {\n    position: relative;\n    height: 30px;\n}\n.range-slider input[type=\"range\"] {\n    position: absolute;\n    width: 100%;\n    -webkit-appearance: none;\n    background: transparent;\n    pointer-events: none;\n}\n.range-slider input[type=\"range\"]::-webkit-slider-thumb {\n    -webkit-appearance: none;\n    height: 16px;\n    width: 16px;\n    border-radius: 50%;\n    background: #3b82f6;\n    pointer-events: auto;\n    cursor: pointer;\n}\n```\n\nJavaScript handler:\n```javascript\nfunction filterByTc(min, max) {\n    const colors = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.color;\n    const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n    \n    materials.forEach((m, i) => {\n        const visible = m.tc >= min && m.tc <= max && clusterVisibility[m.cluster];\n        const color = clusterColors[m.cluster];\n        const alpha = visible ? 1 : 0.03;\n        colors.array[i * 3] = color.r * alpha;\n        colors.array[i * 3 + 1] = color.g * alpha;\n        colors.array[i * 3 + 2] = color.b * alpha;\n        sizes.array[i] = visible ? targetSizes[i] : 0.1;\n    });\n    \n    colors.needsUpdate = true;\n    sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n    \n    // Update visible count\n    const visibleCount = materials.filter(m => m.tc >= min && m.tc <= max).length;\n    document.getElementById('visible-count').textContent = visibleCount.toLocaleString();\n}\n```\n\nThe approach of dimming rather than removing filtered points preserves spatial context -- the scientist can still see where the hidden points were, just faintly.\n\n#### 4B. Click-to-Select with Detail Panel\n\nWhen a user clicks a point (not just hovers), pin the tooltip and show an expanded detail panel.\n\n```javascript\nlet selectedIndex = -1;\n\nrenderer.domElement.addEventListener('click', (event) => {\n    raycaster.setFromCamera(mouse, camera);\n    const intersects = raycaster.intersectObject(pointsMesh);\n    \n    if (intersects.length > 0) {\n        const index = intersects[0].index;\n        selectedIndex = index;\n        const m = materials[index];\n        \n        // Highlight selected point (increase size temporarily)\n        const sizes = pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.size;\n        sizes.array[index] = targetSizes[index] * 3;\n        sizes.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        // Show detail panel\n        showDetailPanel(m, index);\n    } else {\n        clearSelection();\n    }\n});\n```\n\nThe detail panel shows all available properties: `tc`, `atomic_mass`, `atomic_radius`, `valence`, `cluster`, plus the PCA coordinates. For a dataset without material names, the panel should show \"Material #N\" and the numeric properties formatted with units.\n\n#### 4C. Property-Based Search\n\nSince materials have no names, search is by property ranges. Add a collapsible \"Filter\" section:\n\n```html\n<div class=\"control-group\">\n    <div class=\"control-label\">Filter by Properties</div>\n    <div class=\"filter-row\">\n        <label>Atomic Mass</label>\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"mass-min\" placeholder=\"min\" step=\"0.1\">\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"mass-max\" placeholder=\"max\" step=\"0.1\">\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"filter-row\">\n        <label>Atomic Radius</label>\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"radius-min\" placeholder=\"min\" step=\"0.01\">\n        <input type=\"number\" id=\"radius-max\" placeholder=\"max\" step=\"0.01\">\n    </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nThis applies the same color-dimming approach as the Tc slider but across multiple properties simultaneously.\n\n**Budget concern**: This adds ~40 lines of CSS and ~30 lines of JS. If file size is tight, this feature can be deferred in favor of the Tc slider alone, which covers 80% of the use case.\n\n#### 4D. Density Heatmap Toggle\n\n**Approach**: Create a second Points mesh that renders a grid of semi-transparent cubes colored by local density. Precompute a 20x20x20 grid of point counts during data load.\n\n**Decision**: This is the lowest-priority interactive feature. It adds visual complexity without proportional insight, and it competes with the sparse region visualization for visual attention. Recommend deferring unless file size allows. If implemented, make it a toggle that replaces the point cloud temporarily rather than overlaying it.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 5: Code Quality (Effort: Medium, Impact: Professional Impression)\n\n#### 5A. IIFE Wrapper + CONFIG Object\n\nWrap all code in an IIFE as described in section 2.2. Extract magic numbers into a CONFIG object at the top:\n\n```javascript\nconst CONFIG = {\n    SCALE: { x: 60, y: 60, z: 60 },\n    CAMERA: { fov: 50, near: 0.1, far: 1000, default: [80, 60, 80] },\n    BLOOM: { strength: 0.8, radius: 0.4, threshold: 0.85 },\n    ANIMATION: { entryDuration: 2500, cameraDuration: 1000 },\n    GLOW_TC_THRESHOLD: 100,\n    SPARSE_COLOR: 0x22d3ee,\n    CLUSTER_COLORS: [0x3b82f6, 0x8b5cf6, 0xec4899],\n    STAR_COUNT: 1000,\n    RAYCASTER_THRESHOLD: 1\n};\n```\n\n#### 5B. Cache Computed Values\n\nStore `targetSizes` as a module-level Float32Array so the Tc slider and cluster toggle do not need to recompute them. Store `originalColors` similarly. Currently, `toggleCluster()` at line 685 recomputes `originalColors` on every call by mapping over all 21K materials.\n\n```javascript\n// Computed once after point creation:\nconst cachedState = {\n    targetSizes: null,    // Float32Array\n    originalColors: null, // Float32Array (r,g,b per point)\n    positions: null       // Float32Array (x,y,z per point)\n};\n```\n\n#### 5C. Better Error Handling\n\nThe current fetch error handler (line 497) just logs to console and shows a red error div. Add:\n- Retry logic (one retry after 2 seconds)\n- Specific error messages for network vs. JSON parse errors\n- Fallback to show a meaningful message if the data file is missing\n\n```javascript\nasync function loadData() {\n    for (let attempt = 0; attempt < 2; attempt++) {\n        try {\n            const response = await fetch('data/analysis_results.json');\n            if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);\n            const data = await response.json();\n            return data;\n        } catch (e) {\n            if (attempt === 0) {\n                updateLoadingText('Retrying...');\n                await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000));\n            } else {\n                showError(`Failed to load data: ${e.message}`);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 6: Polish (Effort: Low, Impact: Medium)\n\n#### 6A. Cinematic Loading Sequence\n\nReplace the basic spinner with a progress bar and staged messages:\n\n```javascript\nconst loadingMessages = [\n    'Initializing Three.js scene...',\n    'Loading 21,263 superconductors...',\n    'Computing spatial layout...',\n    'Activating bloom post-processing...',\n    'Ready.'\n];\n```\n\nEach message appears as the corresponding initialization step completes. The last message fades out as the entry animation begins.\n\n#### 6B. Smooth Transitions for All State Changes\n\nThe current `toggleCluster()` instantly changes colors. Add interpolation:\n\n```javascript\nfunction animateColorTransition(duration = 300) {\n    const startColors = new Float32Array(currentColors);\n    const startTime = performance.now();\n    \n    function step() {\n        const t = Math.min((performance.now() - startTime) / duration, 1);\n        const eased = easeOutCubic(t);\n        \n        for (let i = 0; i < startColors.length; i++) {\n            currentColors[i] = startColors[i] + (targetColors[i] - startColors[i]) * eased;\n        }\n        pointsMesh.geometry.attributes.color.needsUpdate = true;\n        \n        if (t < 1) requestAnimationFrame(step);\n    }\n    step();\n}\n```\n\nApply this to cluster toggles, Tc range changes, and camera transitions.\n\n#### 6C. Meta Tags, Favicon, Open Graph\n\nAdd to `<head>`:\n```html\n<meta name=\"description\" content=\"Interactive 3D visualization of 21,263 superconductors mapped in composition space. Explore critical temperature patterns, composition families, and under-explored regions.\">\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"SuperSearch - Superconductor Composition Explorer\">\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"21,263 superconductors mapped in 3D. Find where the next breakthrough might be hiding.\">\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https://reubenrunacres.github.io/supersearch/preview.png\">\n<meta name=\"twitter:card\" content=\"summary_large_image\">\n<link rel=\"icon\" href=\"data:image/svg+xml,<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 100 100'><text y='.9em' font-size='90'>🔬</text></svg>\">\n```\n\nThe favicon uses an inline SVG data URI (no external file needed). The og:image requires a screenshot saved as `preview.png`.\n\n#### 6D. Keyboard Shortcut Overlay\n\nShow a floating overlay when the user presses `?`:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {\n    if (e.key === '?') toggleShortcutOverlay();\n    // ... existing shortcuts\n});\n```\n\nThe overlay is a simple `<div>` with `position: fixed` that lists all shortcuts. Style it with the existing glassmorphic panel CSS.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Implementation Sequencing\n\nThe recommended order balances \"ship something impressive fast\" with \"don't create technical debt\":\n\n| Step | Task | Lines Added | Cumulative Size | Impact |\n|------|------|-------------|-----------------|--------|\n| 1 | IIFE wrapper + CONFIG object | +30 | ~29.5 KB | Foundation |\n| 2 | Fix bloom pipeline (add missing CDNs + wire up) | +25 | ~30.2 KB | Huge visual |\n| 3 | Fix extent calculation | -4, +8 | ~30.3 KB | Performance |\n| 4 | Entry animation | +55 | ~31.8 KB | Wow factor |\n| 5 | High-Tc glow halos (second particle layer) | +30 | ~32.7 KB | Visual depth |\n| 6 | Background stars | +15 | ~33.2 KB | Atmosphere |\n| 7 | 3D axis labels (canvas sprites) | +50 | ~34.6 KB | Scientific cred |\n| 8 | Sparse region redesign (cyan wireframe + scan plane) | +40 | ~35.7 KB | Science + visual |\n| 9 | Tc range slider | +60 (CSS+JS+HTML) | ~37.4 KB | Interactivity |\n| 10 | Click-to-select detail panel | +50 | ~38.8 KB | Exploration |\n| 11 | PCA variance annotations | +10 | ~39.1 KB | Science |\n| 12 | Smooth transitions | +25 | ~39.8 KB | Polish |\n| 13 | Cinematic loading | +20 | ~40.4 KB | First impression |\n| 14 | Meta tags + favicon | +15 | ~40.8 KB | SEO/sharing |\n| 15 | Fix mobile responsive | +20 (CSS) | ~41.4 KB | Accessibility |\n| 16 | Keyboard overlay | +30 | ~42.3 KB | Polish |\n| 17 | Cached computed values | +15, -10 | ~42.4 KB | Performance |\n\n**Total estimated final size: ~42 KB** -- well within the 50 KB budget.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Risk Assessment\n\n**Risk 1: Bloom + 21K additive-blended points = washed-out white mess.**\nMitigation: Set bloom threshold to 0.85 so only the bright sprite centers bloom. Test with strength values 0.5-1.0. The fog at line 425 (`FogExp2` density 0.002) will attenuate distant points, preventing global blowout.\n\n**Risk 2: Entry animation conflicts with the existing `animate()` loop.**\nMitigation: The entry animation runs as a separate `requestAnimationFrame` loop that only modifies `sizes.array` and `camera.position`. The main `animate()` loop still handles rendering. Do NOT block the main loop.\n\n**Risk 3: Dual-range slider CSS is finicky cross-browser.**\nMitigation: Use the z-index stacking approach where both inputs overlap. Test on Chrome/Safari/Firefox. If Firefox styling is problematic, fall back to a single range input with a numeric min/max display.\n\n**Risk 4: Canvas text sprites look blurry at certain zoom levels.**\nMitigation: Use 512px wide canvas for text (already specified above). Set `sprite.scale` proportionally. The text will be crisp at the default zoom level and acceptable at 2x zoom. For very close zoom, the sprites can be made to face the camera with `sprite.material.sizeAttenuation = false` but this changes the aesthetic -- test before committing.\n\n**Risk 5: ShaderPass/CopyShader CDN files might not exist for r128.**\nMitigation: The Three.js examples directory for r128 on jsdelivr has been stable since 2021. The files exist at:\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/CopyShader.js`\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/shaders/LuminosityHighPassShader.js`\n- `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/postprocessing/ShaderPass.js`\n\nVerify before deploying. If unavailable, inline the shader code (CopyShader is ~20 lines, LuminosityHighPassShader is ~40 lines).\n\n---\n\n## 6. What NOT to Do\n\n1. **Do not switch to ES modules / import maps.** Three.js r128 via CDN uses the global `THREE` namespace. The import-map approach requires r128+ module builds that have different CDN paths. Stay with the `<script>` tag approach.\n\n2. **Do not add GSAP or tween.js.** The entry animation and transitions are simple enough to implement with `requestAnimationFrame` + easing functions. Adding a 40KB animation library is not justified.\n\n3. **Do not add a search-by-name feature.** The data does not contain material names or formulas. The `material` field checked at line 733 (`material.material || 'Superconductor ' + index`) is undefined for all entries. To add names, the `analyze_data.py` pipeline would need to be modified to include the original formula from the CSV, which is a data pipeline change, not a frontend change.\n\n4. **Do not implement the density heatmap** unless all higher-priority items are done and there is size budget remaining. It is the lowest bang-for-buck feature on the list.\n\n5. **Do not use `CSS2DRenderer`** for axis labels. It adds a CDN dependency, creates DOM elements that don't participate in bloom, and requires a separate render pass.\n\n---\n\n### Critical Files for Implementation\n\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/docs/index.html` - The single self-contained visualization file that must be modified. All 795 lines of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript live here.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/data/analysis_results.json` - The 3.2 MB JSON data source. Understanding its schema (materials array with x/y/tc/cluster/atomic_mass/atomic_radius/valence, sparse_regions array with x/y/density, metadata with pca_variance/tc_range) is essential for every feature.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/analyze_data.py` - The Python pipeline that generates the JSON. Must be modified if better cluster names or material formulas are needed (it currently discards material identity).\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/web-original/index.html` - The original D3.js 2D version. Contains axis label patterns and insight text that should be ported to the 3D version for scientific completeness.\n- `/Users/03-mac-alpha/.openclaw/workspace/supersearch/FOR_PERIODIC_LABS.md` - The pitch document containing cluster descriptions (\"cuprate-like\", \"pnictide-inspired\", \"mixed-metal\") and strategic framing that should inform the visualization's annotations and naming."}],"totalDurationMs":253688,"totalTokens":55204,"totalToolUseCount":30,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":171,"cache_read_input_tokens":44652,"output_tokens":10380,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":171,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
